# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diesel-particulate-filter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The **California Statewide Truck and Bus Rule** was initially adopted in December 2008 by the California Air Resources Board (CARB) and requires all heavy-duty diesel trucks and buses that operate in California to retrofit or replace engines in order to reduce diesel emissions.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] All privately and federally owned diesel-fueled trucks and buses, and privately and publicly owned school buses with a gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR) greater than 14,000 pounds, are covered by the regulation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Implementation was originally scheduled for January 1, 2011 but recent amendments were considered in December 2010.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The rule now requires the installation of particulate matter filters beginning January 1, 2012 and replacement of older engines beginning January 1, 2015.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Nearly all applicable vehicles are required to have 2010 model year or the equivalent to 2010 engines by January 1, 2023.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Diesel exhaust particulate matter (PM) was identified as a toxic air contaminant by the Air Resources Board in 1998 after study results showed its potential to cause cancer, premature death, and other health problems.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] In 2007 the Air Resources Board then adopted a State Implementation Plan (SIP) which requires heavy-duty in-use diesel trucks operating in the South Coast and San Joaquin Valley to be retrofitted to meet model year 2007 emission levels by 2014 and 2017, respectively.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The State Implementation Plan was implemented to help California's Air Quality Control Regions (AQCR) meet the requirements of the Federal Clean Air Act and also aims to reduce nitrogen oxide emissions (NOx) and ozone in the state.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] This regulation is the next step to help the Air Resources Board achieve their goal to reduce diesel particulate matter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] With the new amendments in place, diesel emissions are estimated to be 68 percent lower than they would be without the regulation, and emissions of the smog-forming pollutant, nitrogen oxide, will be 25 percent lower.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The regulation also aims to save lives and dollars spent on health care.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The Air Resources Board estimates that the reduction in diesel emissions is expected to save 9,400 lives within the 11 year time frame and reduce health care costs, with an estimated savings between US$48 billion and $69 billion.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] By the time the rule is fully implemented in 2023, no truck or bus more than 13 years old will be allowed to operate in California without particulate matter and nitrogen oxide emissions controls.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] According to the Union of Concerned Scientists, the retrofits could reduce global warming pollution by 17 million metric tons of carbon dioxide equivalent (CO2e) by 2020 and a net savings of $30,000 over the life of one long-range truck.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] In addition to reducing air pollution, this regulation is thought to have helped broaden and strengthen the environmental movement in California.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Congress, "prohibits any state or any political subdivision from enacting or enforcing any regulation related to the price, route, or service of a motor carrier".
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The California Dump Truck Owners Association also expresses concerns about the regulation because of the costs to retrofit or replace engines and the economic impact it will have on small business owners whose livelihood relies on the income generated by their trucks.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Many of the association's members work closely with the construction industry; therefore, business is already slow during this economic depression.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The association has alerted the Air Resources Board that many small businesses will close down if they cannot afford to comply with the regulation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and the Air Resources Board's conclusions about the health impacts of diesel particulate matter are also disputed.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Other Key Legal Actions & Dates: On October 30, 2013, CCTA received an order from the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeal denying its motion for reconsideration of the ‘en banc’ (full court) petition to review the EPA's determination and approval of the California State Implementation Plan or SIP.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] This was a longshot based on the timing issues, as the SIP was ‘stealthily’ filed and approved during the litigation against CARB.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Related to this is a petition directly to EPA for reconsideration of the approval of the SIP by EPA – again all ‘surreptitiously’ done during direct litigation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] This challenge is more an exercise of thoroughness than legal utility.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The CCTA's main legal action or FAAAA argument claim, stating that state law (CARB regulations) violates federal law is also on Appeal to the Ninth Circuit Court.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The appeal of Judge England's order saying that "he no longer had authority over the case" is still pending and will be appealed ultimately to the U.S.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] 1/16/12 – CCTA files a Notice to Appeal with the 9th Circuit Court.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Does not address any elements of our complaint but instead states that “it cannot retain jurisdiction over this action in light of EPA’s approval of the Truck and Bus Regulation as part of California’s SIP”.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] EPA is now considered an indispensable party to our litigation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] 9/6/12 – Final hearing on our request for relief under the Supremacy Clause (decision pending shortly).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Section 2025 of the rule states that "The purpose of this regulation is to reduce emissions of diesel particulate matter (PM), oxides of nitrogen (NOx) and other criteria pollutants, and greenhouse gases from in-use diesel-fueled vehicles".
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] A percent of the total fleet must meet particulate matter Best Available Control Technology and nitrogen oxide Best Available Control Technology by January 1 of each compliance year, by retrofitting or replacing existing diesel vehicles.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The fleet must meet an average requirement set by the Air Resources Board for particulate matter, nitrogen oxide, or both pollutants, depending on the Nitrogen Oxide Index and Particulate Matter Index established by CARB.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] These regulations apply to any business, person, federal government agency or school district that owns, operates, sells or runs vehicles operated on diesel-fuel.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] In order to assist truck owners to meet the standards of the regulation, the Air Resources Board provides compliance tools on their website.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] An Excel spreadsheet called the “Fleet Calculator” assists owners to comply with the truck and bus rule.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The owners can determine what type of compliance options may be available by inputting engine model year and emission control technology assumptions into the calculator.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The tool follows regulation amendments, and a hotline has been set up for fleet owners called the Air Resources Board's Diesel Hotline.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The system utilized for reporting is the Truck Regulations Upload and Compliance Reporting System (TRUCRS).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Reporting guidelines are not required until 2012, however fleets can take advantage of Agricultural Vehicle Provisions or to meet requirements for Tier 0 auxiliary engines in street sweepers.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] By April 29, 2011, these previously mentioned two-engine street sweepers have to start reporting hourly meter readings beginning January 1, 2011.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] In order to meet these guidelines, reports can be made online or in paper format.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Also by April 29, 2011, those fleets that reported Agricultural Provisions in the previous year can update their January 1, 2011 odometer readings in order to qualify for Agricultural Vehicle Provisions.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Annual reporting will be mandatory as of January 31, 2012.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] All fleet owners may submit reporting materials using paper or electronic forms reporting annually until the expiration of requirements or until the year after Best Available Control Technology.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Owner contact and vehicle information including but not limited to type, gross vehicle weight rating and model year are mandatory as a part of reporting.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Engine information, verified diesel emission control strategies (VDECS), and highest available VDECS must also be submitted into reporting.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Low-use vehicles, fleets claiming vehicle retirement credits, school bus fleets/sub-fleets, agricultural fleets, vehicles exempt from NOx BACT and emergency support vehicles have their own specified reporting conditions which coincide and build onto the overall reporting requirements.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] All reports must submit compliance certification signed by a responsible official or a designee to confirm that the reporting is accurate prior to submission to the executive officer.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] If there are any changes since the last reporting, the responsible party must report it to the executive officer.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] These changes include vehicles that may be removed or added to the fleet or those vehicles that have recently been repowered or retrofitted.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] New fleet reporting for those that elect to use the Best Available Control Technology percent limits must also submit information to the executive officer.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Operators of diesel vehicles and equipment must install Diesel Emission Control Strategies (DECS) to new and existing engines in order to comply with the regulation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] DECS are technology-based retrofits that reduce pollutants from diesel exhaust before they are released into the air.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] A commonly used DECS technology is the diesel particulate filter which serves as a substitution for an engine's original factory muffler.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] All Diesel Emission Control Strategies must be verified and approved by the Air Resources Board to ensure proper particulate matter and nitrogen oxide reductions will be met.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Diesel truck emissions include smog-forming nitrogen oxide and are the largest source of diesel particulate matter which is known to cause harm to the lungs, the immune system, the heart and cardiovascular system, and the developing brain.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Seventy percent of California's risk for cancer from airborne toxics in 2000 was attributed to diesel particulate matter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] In 2004 it was estimated that premature death rates from diesel pollution would supersede the death rates from homicides that year.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] It is projected that reducing emissions today would prevent 11,000 premature deaths and 16,000 hospital admissions by 2020.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The cost-benefit analysis of reducing diesel pollution concluded with the results that small costs of pollution cleanup can drastically cut health-related costs, such as reduced hospitalization.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The areas of California with the highest health related risks in exposure to diesel pollution are those that are the most densely populated air basins.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] Half of California's diesel pollution illnesses occur in the South Coast.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] 45% of the State's population resides here, and they breathe 30% of particulate matter and nitrogen oxide (NOx).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The South Coast's projected cost of health impacts is totaled at $10.2 billion per year.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The San Francisco Bay Area is the second most highly affected region in California taking in 17% of the state's diesel pollution.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/2008-california-statewide-truck-and-bus-rule] The estimated health related costs for the Bay Area are $3.7 billion per year.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The **3M Company** (originally the **Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Company**) is an American multinational conglomerate operating in the fields of industry, worker safety, and consumer goods.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Among its best-known consumer brands are Scotch Tape, Scotchgard surface protectants, Post-it notes, and Nexcare adhesive bandages.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M's stock ticker symbol is MMM and is listed on the New York Stock Exchange, Inc.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M made $35.4 billion in total sales in 2021 and ranked number 102 in the *Fortune* 500 list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] As of 2021, the company had approximately 95,000 employees and operations in more than 70 countries.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] There are a few international subsidiaries, such as 3M India, 3M Japan, and 3M Canada.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Five businessmen founded the Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Company as a mining venture in Two Harbors, Minnesota, making their first sale on June 13, 1902.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The goal was to mine corundum, a crystalline form of aluminium oxide, which failed because the mine's mineral holdings were anorthosite, a feldspar which had no commercial value.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Co-founder John Dwan solicited funds in exchange for stock and Edgar Ober and Lucius Ordway took over the company in 1905.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The company moved to Duluth and began researching and producing sandpaper products.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] McKnight, later a key executive, joined the company in 1907, and A.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M finally became financially stable in 1916 and was able to pay dividends.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The company moved to Saint Paul in 1910, where it remained for 52 years before outgrowing the campus and moving to its current headquarters at 3M Center in Maplewood, Minnesota, in 1962.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 1947, 3M began producing perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), an industrial surfactant and chemical feedstock, by electrochemical fluorination.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 1951, DuPont purchased PFOA from then-Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Company for use in the manufacturing of teflon, a product that brought DuPont a billion-dollar-a-year profit by the 1990s.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The original formula for Scotchgard, a water repellent applied to fabrics, was discovered accidentally in 1952 by 3M chemists Patsy Sherman and Samuel Smith.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Sales began in 1956, and in 1973 the two chemists received a patent for the formula.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In the late 1950s, 3M produced the first asthma inhaler, but the company did not enter the pharmaceutical industry until the mid-1960s with the acquisition of Riker Laboratories, moving it from California to Minnesota.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M retained the Riker Laboratories name for the subsidiary until at least 1985.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In the mid-1990s, 3M Pharmaceuticals, as the division came to be called, produced the first CFC-free asthma inhaler in response to adoption of the Montreal Protocol by the United States.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In the 1980s and 1990s, the company spent fifteen years developing a topical cream delivery technology which led in 1997 to health authority approval and marketing of a symptomatic treatment for genital warts, Aldara.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M divested its pharmaceutical unit through three deals in 2006, netting more than US$2 billion.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] At the time, 3M Pharmaceuticals comprised about 20% of 3M's healthcare business and employed just over a thousand people.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] By the 1970s, 3M developed a theatrical blood formula based on red colorfast microbeads suspended in a carrier liquid.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] This stage blood was sold as Nextel Simulated Blood and was used during the production of the 1978 film *Dawn of the Dead*.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In the late 1970s, 3M Mincom was involved in some of the first digital audio recordings to see commercial release when a prototype machine was brought to the Sound 80 studios in Minneapolis.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 1979 3M introduced a digital audio recording system called "3M Digital Audio Mastering System".
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M launched "Press 'n Peel", a sticky bookmark page holder in stores in four cities in 1977, but the results were disappointing.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] A year later 3M instead issued free samples of the product as a sticky note directly to consumers in Boise, Idaho, with 95% of those who tried them indicating they would buy it.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The product was introduced as "Post-Its" in 1979, and was sold across the United States from April 6, 1980.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The following year they were launched in Canada and Europe.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 1980, the company acquired Comtal, a manufacturer of digital image processors.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 1996, the company's data storage and imaging divisions were spun off as Imation Corporation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In doing so, 3M shed 20% of its sales, employees and product lines at a cost of only 5% of its profits and immediately looked much improved in the estimation of Wall Street analysts.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] These businesses, with annual sales of over $2 billion, had generated handsome profits for 3M which funded the research and development of many new product lines, but these were largely in "sunset" industries: printing products, photographic film, and removable storage media.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Imation shortly sold its imaging and photographic film businesses largely to Kodak in order to concentrate on storage.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Imation was purchased by a hedge fund in 2016 and ceased to exist as an independent business.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Its successor is now called Glassbridge Enterprises, an American holding company.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] On April 8, 2002, 3M's 100th anniversary, the company changed its legal name to "3M Company".
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] On September 8, 2008, 3M announced an agreement to acquire Meguiar's, a car-care products company that was family-owned for over a century.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In August 2010, 3M acquired Cogent Systems for $943 million, and on October 13, 2010, 3M completed acquisition of Arizant Inc.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In December 2011, 3M completed the acquisition of the Winterthur Technology Group, a bonded abrasives company.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2011, 3M created CloudLibrary as part of its library systems unit as a competitor to OverDrive, Inc.; in 2015 3M sold the North American part of that unit to Bibliotheca Group GmbH, a company founded in 2011 that was funded by One Equity Partners Capital Advisors, a division of JP Morgan Chase.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] As of 2012, 3M was one of the 30 companies included in the Dow Jones Industrial Average, added on August 9, 1976, and was 97 on the 2011 Fortune 500 list.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] On January 3, 2012, it was announced that the Office and Consumer Products Division of Avery Dennison was being bought by 3M for $550 million.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The transaction was canceled by 3M in September 2012 amid antitrust concerns.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In May 2013, 3M sold Scientific Anglers and Ross Reels to Orvis.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Ross Reels had been acquired by 3M in 2010.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In March 2017, 3M purchased Johnson Controls International Plc's safety gear business, Scott Safety, for $2 billion.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2017, 3M had net sales for the year of $31.657 billion, up from $30.109 billion the year before.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2018, it was reported that the company would pay $850 million to end the Minnesota water pollution case concerning perfluorochemicals.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Roman was appointed CEO by the board of directors.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] On December 19, 2018, 3M announced it had entered into a definitive agreement to acquire the technology business of M*Modal, for a total enterprise value of $1.0 billion.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In October 2019, 3M purchased Acelity and its KCI subsidiaries for $6.7 billion, including assumption of debt and other adjustments.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] On May 1, 2020, 3M divested substantially all of its drug delivery business to an affiliate of Altaris Capital Partners, LLC. for approximately $650 million, including a 17% interest in the new operating company, Kindeva Drug Delivery.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In December 2021, 3M announced that it would merge its food-safety business with food testing and animal healthcare products maker Neogen.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The deal, with an enterprise value of about $5.3 billion, closed in September 2022.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In July 2022, the company announced it would spin off its healthcare assets to form a new, independent firm, likely completing the transaction in 2023.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M will retain an ownership stake of 19.9% in the new, publicly traded health care company and gradually divest the holdings.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The company will be known as Solventum Corporation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In December 2022, the company announced plans to stop producing and using so-called forever chemicals (per and polyfluoroalkyl), which have been commonly used in items such as food packaging, cellphones, nonstick pans, firefighting foams, and clothing.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] These chemicals are well known for their water-resistant and nonstick properties, but they are also dangerous pollutants that are linked to serious health problems, including ulcerative colitis and cancer.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The move comes as governments in the Netherlands and the United States consider actions against 3M.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In March 2024, 3M announced the appointment of William "Bill" Brown as chief executive officer to take effect on May 1, 2024.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Michael Roman would remain in the role of executive chairman.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Brown, 61, is the former chairman of the board and chief executive officer of L3Harris Technologies.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] As of 2019, 3M produces approximately 60,000 products, and has four business groups focused on safety and industrial, transportation and electronics, health care, and consumer products.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M obtained its first patent in 1924 and acquires approximately 3,000 new patents annually.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The company surpassed the 100,000-patent threshold in 2014.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M's Pollution Prevention Pays (3P) program was established in 1975.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The program initially focused on pollution reduction at the plant level and was expanded to promote recycling and reduce waste across all divisions in 1989.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] By the early 1990s, approximately 2,500 3P projects decreased the company's total global pollutant generation by 50 percent and saved 3M $500–600 million by eliminating the production of waste requiring subsequent treatment.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 1983, the Oakdale Dump in Oakdale, Minnesota, was listed as an EPA Superfund site after significant groundwater and soil contamination by VOCs and heavy metals was uncovered.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The Oakdale Dump was a 3M dumping site utilized through the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] During the 1990s and 2000s, 3M reduced releases of toxic pollutants by 99 percent and greenhouse gas emissions by 72 percent.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] As of 2012, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) had awarded 3M with the Energy Star Award each year that it has been presented.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 1999, the EPA began investigating perfluorinated chemicals after receiving data on the global distribution and toxicity of perfluorooctanesulfonic acid (PFOS).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] These materials are part of a broad group of perfluoroalkyl and polyfluoroalkyl substances often referred to as PFAS, each of which has different chemical properties.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M, the former primary producer of PFOS from the U.S., announced the phase-out of PFOS, perfluorooctanoic acid, and PFOS-related product production in May 2000.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Perfluorinated compounds produced by 3M have been used in non-stick cookware, stain-resistant fabrics, and other products.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The Cottage Grove facility manufactured PFAS from the 1940s to 2002.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In response to PFAS contamination of the Mississippi River and surrounding area, 3M stated the area will be "cleaned through a combination of groundwater pump-out wells and soil sediment excavation".
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The restoration plan was based on an analysis of the company property and surrounding lands.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The on-site water treatment facility that handled the plant's post-production water was not capable of removing PFAS, which were released into the nearby Mississippi River.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The clean-up cost estimate, which included a granular activated carbon system to remove PFAS from the ground water was $50 to $56 million, funded from a $147 million environmental reserve set aside in 2006.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2008, 3M created the Renewable Energy Division within 3M's Industrial and Transportation Business to focus on Energy Generation and Energy Management.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In late 2010, the state of Minnesota sued 3M for $5 billion in punitive damages, claiming they released PFCs—classified a toxic chemical by the EPA—into local waterways.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] A settlement for $850 million was reached in February 2018.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2019, 3M, along with the Chemours Company and DuPont, appeared before lawmakers to deny responsibility, with company Senior VP of Corporate Affairs Denise Rutherford arguing that the chemicals pose no human health threats at current levels and that there were no victims.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2021, research had determined that 3M's Zwijndrecht (Belgium) factory caused PFOS pollution that may be contaminating agricultural products within a 15 kilometer radius of the plant which includes Antwerp.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The Flemish Government has paid 63 million euros for cleanup costs so far with 3M contributing 75,000 euros.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The Flemish Government issued measures advising against the consumption of, for example, home-grown eggs within a radius of 5 kilometers.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2023, 3M reached an agreement to pay a $10.3bn settlement with numerous US public water systems to resolve thousands of lawsuits over PFAS contamination.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In May 2026, the Australian government launched legal action against 3M, alleging that the company made false statements regarding the long-term environmental impacts of firefighting foam containing PFAS.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The government is seeking more than A$2 billion in damages to recover costs incurred in investigating and managing contamination resulting from the use of the foam.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The government described the lawsuit as the largest legal claim ever brought by Australia.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Assistant Defence Minister Peter Khalil stated that 28 defence sites across Australia had been impacted by PFAS contamination.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M reported total CO2e emissions (direct and indirect) for the twelve months ending December 31, 2020, at 5,280 Kt (-550 /-9.4% y-o-y) and plans to reduce emissions by 50% by 2030 compared to 2019.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The company also aims to achieve carbon neutrality by 2050.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The Combat Arms Earplugs, Version 2 (CAEv2), was developed by Aearo Technologies for U.S. military and civilian use.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The CAEv2 was a double ended earplug that 3M claimed would offer users different levels of protection.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Between 2003 and 2015, these earplugs were standard issue to members of the U.S. military.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In May 2016, Moldex-Metric, Inc., a 3M competitor, filed a whistleblower complaint against 3M under the False Claims Act.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Moldex-Metric claimed that 3M made false claims to the U.S. government about the safety of its earplugs and that it knew the earplugs had an inherently defective design.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In 2018, 3M agreed to pay $9.1 million to the U.S. government to resolve the allegations, without admitting liability.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Since 2018, more than 140,000 former users of the earplugs (primarily U.S. military veterans) have filed suit against 3M claiming they suffer from hearing loss, tinnitus, and other damage as a consequence of the defective design.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Internal emails showed that 3M officials boasted about charging $7.63 per piece for the earplugs which cost 85 cents to produce.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The company's official response indicated that the cost to the government includes R&D costs.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M settled close to 260,000 lawsuits in August 2023 by agreeing to pay $6 billion to current and former U.S. military members who were affected.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The N95 respirator mask was developed by 3M and approved in 1972.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Due to its ability to filter viral particulates, its use was recommended during the COVID-19 pandemic but supply soon became short.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Much of the company's supply had already been sold prior to the outbreak.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The shortages led to the U.S. government asking 3M to stop exporting US-made N95 respirator masks to Canada and to Latin American countries, and President Donald Trump invoked the Defense Production Act to require 3M to prioritize orders from the federal government.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] The dispute was resolved when 3M agreed to import more respirators, mostly from its factories in China.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M later struck a CA$70M deal with the federal government of Canada and the Ontario provincial government to produce N95 masks at their plant in Brockville, Ontario.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M's general offices, corporate research laboratories, and some division laboratories in the U.S. are in St.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] In the United States, 3M operates 80 manufacturing facilities in 29 states, and 125 manufacturing and converting facilities in 37 countries outside the U.S.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] During March 2016, 3M completed a 400,000-square-foot (37,000 m2) research-and-development building on its Maplewood campus that cost $150 million.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] Seven hundred scientists from various divisions occupy the building.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] They were previously scattered across the campus.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M hopes concentrating its research and development in this manner will improve collaboration.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/3m] 3M received $9.6 million in local tax increment financing and relief from state sales taxes in order to assist with development of the building.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/air-pollution] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] A **diesel particulate filter** (**DPF**) is a device designed to remove diesel particulate matter or soot from the exhaust gas of a diesel engine.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Wall-flow diesel particulate filters usually remove 85% or more of the soot, and under certain conditions can attain soot removal efficiencies approaching 100%.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Some filters are single-use, intended for disposal and replacement once full of accumulated ash.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Others are designed to burn off the accumulated particulate either passively through the use of a catalyst or by active means such as a fuel burner which heats the filter to soot combustion temperatures.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Cleaning is also required as part of periodic maintenance, and it must be done carefully to avoid damaging the filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Failure of fuel injectors or turbochargers resulting in contamination of the filter with raw diesel or engine oil can also necessitate cleaning.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The regeneration process occurs at road speeds higher than can generally be attained on city streets; vehicles driven exclusively at low speeds in urban traffic can require periodic trips at higher speeds to clean out the DPF.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] If the driver ignores the warning light and waits too long to operate the vehicle above 60 km/h (40 mph), the DPF may not regenerate properly, and continued operation past that point may spoil the DPF completely so it must be replaced.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Some newer diesel engines, namely those installed in combination vehicles, can also perform what is called a Parked Regeneration, where the engine increases RPM to around 1400 while parked, to increase the temperature of the exhaust.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Diesel engines produce a variety of particles during the combustion of the fuel/air mix due to incomplete combustion.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The composition of the particles varies widely dependent upon engine type, age, and the emissions specification that the engine was designed to meet.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Two-stroke diesel engines produce more particulate per unit of power than do four-stroke diesel engines, as they burn the fuel-air mix less completely.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Diesel particulate matter resulting from the incomplete combustion of diesel fuel produces soot (black carbon) particles.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] These particles include tiny nanoparticles—smaller than one micrometre (one micron).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Soot and other particles from diesel engines worsen the particulate matter pollution in the air and are harmful to health.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] New particulate filters can capture from 30% to greater than 95% of the harmful soot.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] With an optimal diesel particulate filter (DPF), soot emissions may be decreased to 0.001 g/km or less.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Diesel particulate filtering was first considered in the 1970s due to concerns regarding the impacts of inhaled particulates.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Particulate filters have been in use on non-road machines since 1980, and in automobiles since 1985.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Historically medium and heavy duty diesel engine emissions were not regulated until 1987 when the first California Heavy Truck rule was introduced capping particulate emissions at 0.60 g/BHP Hour.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Since then, progressively tighter standards have been introduced for light- and heavy-duty road-going diesel-powered vehicles and for off-road diesel engines.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Similar regulations have also been adopted by the European Union and some individual European countries, most Asian countries, and the rest of North and South America.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Whilst few jurisdictions have explicitly made filters mandatory, the increasingly stringent emissions regulations that engine manufacturers must meet mean that eventually all on-road diesel engines will be fitted with them.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In the European Union, filters are highly recommended and effectively necessary to meet the Euro 6 Heavy-Duty emissions standards for vehicles such as lorries.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In 2000, in anticipation of the future Euro 5 regulations PSA Peugeot Citroën became the first company to make filters standard on passenger cars.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Euro 5 regulations, fully coming into force in January 2011, require that diesel cars must have a diesel particulate filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Retrofitting the engines with CARB-approved diesel particulate filters is one way to fulfil this requirement.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In 2009 the *American Recovery and Reinvestment Act* provided funding to assist owners in offsetting the cost of diesel retrofits for their vehicles.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Inadequately maintained particulate filters on vehicles with diesel engines are prone to soot buildup, which can cause engine problems due to high back pressure.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In 2018, the UK made changes to its MOT test requirements, including tougher scrutiny of diesel cars.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] One requirement was to have a properly fitted and working DPF.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Driving without a DPF could incur a £1000 fine.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Unlike a catalytic converter which is a flow-through device, a DPF retains bigger exhaust gas particles by forcing the gas to flow through the filter material before exiting; however, the DPF does not retain small particles.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Maintenance-free DPFs oxidise or burn larger particles until they are small enough to pass through the filter, though often particles "clump" together in the DPF reducing the overall particle count as well as overall mass.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] There are a variety of diesel particulate filter technologies on the market.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The most common filter is made of cordierite (a ceramic material that is also used as catalytic converter supports (cores)).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Cordierite filters provide excellent filtration efficiency, are relatively inexpensive, and have thermal properties that make packaging them for installation in the vehicle simple.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The major drawback is that cordierite has a relatively low melting point (about 1200 °C) and cordierite substrates have been known to melt during filter regeneration.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This is mostly an issue if the filter has become loaded more heavily than usual, and is more of an issue with passive systems than with active systems, unless there is a system breakdown.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Cordierite filter cores look like catalytic converter cores that have had alternate channels plugged – the plugs force the exhaust gas flow through the wall and the particulate collects on the inlet face.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The second most popular filter material is silicon carbide, or SiC.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] It has a higher (2700 °C) melting point than cordierite, however, it is not as stable thermally, making packaging an issue.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Small SiC cores are made of single pieces, while larger cores are made in segments, which are separated by a special cement so that heat expansion of the core will be taken up by the cement, and not the package.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] SiC cores are usually more expensive than cordierite cores, however they are manufactured in similar sizes, and one can often be used to replace the other.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Silicon carbide filter cores also look like catalytic converter cores that have had alternate channels plugged – again the plugs force the exhaust gas flow through the wall and the particulate collects on the inlet face.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Fibrous ceramic filters are made from several different types of ceramic fibers that are mixed together to form a porous medium.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This medium can be formed into almost any shape and can be customized to suit various applications.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The porosity can be controlled in order to produce high flow, lower efficiency or high efficiency lower volume filtration.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Fibrous filters have an advantage over wall flow design of producing lower back pressure.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Fibrous ceramic filters remove carbon particulates almost completely, including fine particulates less than 100 nanometres (nm) diameter with an efficiency of greater than 95% in mass and greater than 99% in number of particles over a wide range of engine operating conditions.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Since the continuous flow of soot into the filter would eventually block it, it is necessary to 'regenerate' the filtration properties of the filter by burning off the collected particulate on a regular basis.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Soot particulate burn-off forms water and CO2 in small quantities amounting to less than 0.05% of the CO2 emitted by the engine.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Some cores are made from metal fibers – generally the fibers are "woven" into a monolith.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Such cores have the advantage that an electrical current can be passed through the monolith to heat the core for regeneration purposes, allowing the filter to regenerate at low exhaust temperatures and/or low exhaust flow rates.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Metal fiber cores tend to be more expensive than cordierite or silicon carbide cores, and are generally not interchangeable with them because of the electrical requirement.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Disposable paper cores are used in certain specialty applications, without a regeneration strategy.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Coal mines are common users – the exhaust gas is usually first passed through a water trap to cool it, and then through the filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Paper filters are also used when a diesel machine must be used indoors for short periods of time, such as on a forklift being used to install equipment inside a store.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] There are a variety of devices that produce over 50% particulate matter filtration, but less than 85%.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Partial filters come in a variety of materials.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The only commonality between them is that they produce more back pressure than a catalytic converter, and less than a diesel particulate filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Partial filter technology is popular for retrofit.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Filters require more maintenance than catalytic converters.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Ash, a byproduct of oil consumption from normal engine operation, builds up in the filter as it cannot be converted into a gas and pass through the walls of the filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This increases the pressure before the filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] DPF filters go through a regeneration process which removes this soot and lowers the filter pressure.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] There are three types of regeneration: passive, active, and forced.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Passive regeneration takes place normally while driving, when engine load and vehicle drive-cycle create temperatures that are high enough to regenerate the soot buildup on the DPF walls.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Active regeneration happens while the vehicle is in use, when low engine load and lower exhaust gas temperatures inhibit the naturally occurring passive regeneration.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Sensors upstream and downstream of the DPF (or a differential pressure sensor) provide readings that initiate a metered addition of fuel into the exhaust stream.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] There are two methods to inject fuel, either downstream injection directly into the exhaust stream, downstream of the turbo, or fuel injection into the engine cylinders on the exhaust stroke.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This fuel and exhaust gas mixture passes through the Diesel Oxidation Catalyst (DOC) creating temperatures high enough to burn off the accumulated soot.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Once the pressure drop across the DPF lowers to a calculated value, the process ends, until the soot accumulation builds up again.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This works well for vehicles that drive longer distances with few stops compared to those that perform short trips with many starts and stops.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] If the filter develops too much pressure then the last type of regeneration must be used – a forced regeneration.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The vehicle operator can initiate the regeneration via a dashboard mounted switch.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Various signal interlocks, such as park brake applied, transmission in neutral, engine coolant temperature, and an absence of engine related fault codes are required (vary by OEM and application) for this process to initiate.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] When the soot accumulation reaches a level that is potentially damaging to the engine or the exhaust system, the solution involves a garage using a computer program to run a regeneration of the DPF manually using a diagnostic scan tool.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] When a regeneration occurs, the soot is turned to gasses and ash of which some remains in the filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This will increase restriction through the filter and can result in a blockage.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Warnings are given to the driver before filter restriction causes an issue with driveability or damage to the engine or filter develop.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Regular filter maintenance is a necessity to remove ash build up, either through cleaning or replacement of the filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Regeneration typically requires the vehicle to be driven continuously at 50-60mph (80-100km/h) for 30 to 45 minutes every few hundred miles/kilometers of city driving.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Heavy duty pickup trucks have less stringent requirements for all three parameters, and Class 8 trucks significantly less.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] If the vehicle is often driven in cities the DPF may become clogged, causing a reduction in power and acceleration either passively due to increased exhaust pressure or actively due to vehicle going into "limp/turtle mode" as it tries to prevent engine and turbo damage.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Once clogged both passive and active regeneration may become ineffective.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] DPF may be unclogged by high temperature pressure washing (not officially recommended) and/or burn-off oven.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In 2011, Ford recalled 37,400 F-Series trucks with diesel engines after fuel and oil leaks caused fires in the diesel particulate filters of the trucks.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] No injuries occurred before the recall, though one grass fire was started.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] A similar recall was issued for 2005-2007 Jaguar S-Type and XJ diesels, where large amounts of soot became trapped in the DPF In affected vehicles, smoke and fire emanated from the vehicle underside, accompanied by flames from the rear of the exhaust.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The heat from the fire could cause heating through the transmission tunnel to the interior, melting interior components and potentially causing interior fires.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Regeneration is the process of burning off (oxidizing) the accumulated soot from the filter.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This is done either passively (from the engine's exhaust heat in normal operation or by adding a catalyst to the filter) or actively introducing very high heat into the exhaust system.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] All on-board active systems use extra fuel, whether through burning to heat the DPF, or providing extra power to the DPF's electrical system, although the use of a fuel borne catalyst reduces the energy required very significantly.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Typically a computer monitors one or more sensors that measure back pressure and/or temperature, and based on pre-programmed set points the computer makes decisions on when to activate the regeneration cycle.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The additional fuel can be supplied by a metering pump.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Running the cycle too often while keeping the back pressure in the exhaust system low will result in high fuel consumption.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Not running the regeneration cycle soon enough increases the risk of engine damage and/or uncontrolled regeneration (thermal runaway) and possible DPF failure.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Diesel particulate matter burns when temperatures above 600 °C are attained.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This temperature can be reduced to somewhere in the range of 350 to 450 °C by use of a fuel-borne catalyst.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The actual temperature of soot burn-out will depend on the chemistry employed.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In the mid-2010s, scientists at 3M developed a magnesium doped version of traditional iron based catalysts which lowered the temperature required for particulate matter oxidation to just over 200 °C.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The lower reaction temperature is made possible by the dopant allowing the Fe lattice to hold more oxygen.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] This advancement is significant because it allows the cleaning reaction to take place at the standard operating temperature of most diesel engines, removing the requirement for burning extra fuel or otherwise artificially heating the engine.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The family of Mg doped catalysts, named Grindstaff catalysts after the chemist who started the work, has been the subject of much investigation across industry and academia with the tightening of emissions regulations on particulate matter world wide.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In some cases, in the absence of a fuel-borne catalyst, the combustion of the particulate matter can raise temperatures so high, that they are above the structural integrity threshold of the filter material, which can cause catastrophic failure of the substrate.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Various strategies have been developed to limit this possibility.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Note that unlike a spark-ignited engine, which typically has less than 0.5% oxygen in the exhaust gas stream before the emission control device(s), diesel engines have a very high ratio of oxygen available.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] While the amount of available oxygen makes fast regeneration of a filter possible, it also contributes to runaway regeneration problems.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Some applications use off-board regeneration.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Off-board regeneration requires operator intervention (i.e. the machine is either plugged into a wall/floor mounted regeneration station, or the filter is removed from the machine and placed in the regeneration station).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Off-board regeneration is not suitable for on-road vehicles, except in situations where the vehicles are parked in a central depot when not in use.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Off-board regeneration is mainly used in industrial and mining applications.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Coal mines (with the attendant explosion risk from coal damp) use off-board regeneration if non-disposable filters are installed, with the regeneration stations sited in an area where non-permissible machinery is allowed.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Many forklifts may also use off-board regeneration – typically mining machinery and other machinery that spend their operational lives in one location, which makes having a stationary regeneration station practical.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] In situations where the filter is physically removed from the machine for regeneration there is also the advantage of being able to inspect the filter core on a daily basis (DPF cores for non-road applications are typically sized to be usable for one shift – so regeneration is a daily occurrence).
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] Intentionally removing or tampering with a DPF is prohibited by the EPA.
[src:diesel-particulate-filter/diesel-particulate-filter] The act of removing emission control devices, such as a DPF, is commonly referred to as "deleting." Several manufacturers and retailers of diesel emissions defeat devices have been fined up to $1 million.
